in the body. When protein C is activated by thrombin bound to thrombomodulin, it forms a complex with protein S, which acts as a cofactor. This complex specifically inactivates \u003Cstrong\u003Efactors Va and VIIIa\u003C/strong\u003E, which are crucial for the amplification of the coagulation cascade. By inactivating these factors, the protein C-protein S complex helps to regulate and limit clot formation, preventing excessive coagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactors XIa and XIIa\u003C/strong\u003E are involved in the intrinsic pathway of the coagulation cascade, but they are not directly inactivated by the protein C-protein S complex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactors Va and VIIa\u003C/strong\u003E are not a pair that is inactivated by the protein C-protein S complex. Factor VIIa is part of the extrinsic pathway and is not targeted by this complex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactors VIIa and VIIIa\u003C/strong\u003E are not both inactivated by the protein C-protein S complex. While factor VIIIa is inactivated, factor VIIa is not.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactors VIa and VIIIa\u003C/strong\u003E is not a correct pair, as factor VI is not a recognised factor in the coagulation cascade. Factor VIIIa is inactivated by the protein C-protein S complex, but factor VIa is not relevant.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The protein C-protein S complex inactivates coagulation factors Va and VIIIa, which are essential for the amplification of the coagulation cascade.","Protein C is activated by thrombin bound to thrombomodulin, and its anticoagulant effect is enhanced by protein S.","The inactivation of factors Va and VIIIa by the protein C-protein S complex helps regulate and limit clot formation."],"references":["Kitchens, C. S., Konkle, B. A., \u0026 Kessler, C. M. (2013). Consultative Hemostasis and Thrombosis: Expert Consult-Online and Print. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., Fausto, N., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (2014). Robbins and Cotran pathologic basis of disease, professional edition e-book. Elsevier health sciences","Chaudhry R, Usama SM, Babiker HM. Physiology, Coagulation Pathways. [Updated 2023 Aug 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482253/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44290"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14834"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44290"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-03T12:50:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T19:07:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7525"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58882"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}}